<TITLE> Budget session of Parliament reconvenes, hits snag </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 NEW DELHI, Apr 15 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Opposition protests over a raft of issues briefly shut the reopening of the parliament on Thursday, signalling a difficult session ahead for the government as it seeks to pass the budget and other key bills. Major opposition parties have said they will seek a special vote on high food prices which would force the government to resign if it loses it. No date has been set yet for the vote. On Thursday when parliament reconvened after a month's recess, opposition members disrupted proceedings demanding a discussion on Maoist rebel attacks earlier this month which killed more than 70 security personnel. Opposition parties are also expected to criticise the government amid allegations of corruption against a junior minister. All this is expected to delay discussions on the budget and other important bills at a time when the government is at its weakest since re-election last year after two of its allies withdrew support over a bill reserving parliamentary seats for women. There is no immediate threat to the government over the budget bill. But reduced parliamentary support means the government will concentrate on ensuring the budget is passed rather than focus its energies on other reform bil
